Here are the three in turn, each with its denominator free of radicals:

a) \(\displaystyle \frac1{\sqrt[4]7}\)

Multiply top and bottom by \(\sqrt[4]{7^3}\).  Then
\[
\frac1{\sqrt[4]7}
\;\times\;
\frac{\sqrt[4]{7^3}}{\sqrt[4]{7^3}}
\;=\;
\frac{\sqrt[4]{7^3}}{\sqrt[4]{7^4}}
\;=\;
\frac{\sqrt[4]{343}}{7}\,. 
\]

b) \(\displaystyle \sqrt[4]{\frac5{32}}\)

Write it as \(\frac{\sqrt[4]5}{\sqrt[4]{32}}\) and multiply top and bottom by \(\sqrt[4]{8}\) (since \(32\cdot8=256=4^4\)):
\[
\sqrt[4]{\frac5{32}}
=\frac{\sqrt[4]5}{\sqrt[4]{32}}
\;\times\;
\frac{\sqrt[4]8}{\sqrt[4]8}
=
\frac{\sqrt[4]{40}}{\sqrt[4]{256}}
=
\frac{\sqrt[4]{40}}{4}\,. 
\]

You can also note \(\sqrt[4]{40}=\sqrt2\,\sqrt[4]5\), so an equivalent form is \(\tfrac{\sqrt2\,\sqrt[4]5}{4}.\)

c) \(\displaystyle \frac{4}{\sqrt[4]{4x^2}}\)

Method 1: Observe \(\sqrt[4]{4x^2}=\sqrt2\;\sqrt{x}\), so
\[
\frac{4}{\sqrt2\,\sqrt x}
=\frac{4}{\sqrt{2x}}
\;\times\;
\frac{\sqrt{2x}}{\sqrt{2x}}
=
\frac{4\sqrt{2x}}{2x}
=
\frac{2\sqrt{2x}}x\,.
\]

Method 2 (pure 4th‐root approach): multiply top and bottom by \(\sqrt[4]{(4x^2)^3}\) to get the same result,
\[
\frac{4}{\sqrt[4]{4x^2}}
\;\times\;
\frac{\sqrt[4]{(4x^2)^3}}{\sqrt[4]{(4x^2)^3}}
=
\frac{4\,\sqrt[4]{(4x^2)^3}}{4x^2}
=
\frac{2\sqrt{2x}}x\,. 
\]

